{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486937"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:50:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.03,0.08,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68011"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"253"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28324"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is being assessed on day one following an emergency laparotomy for small bowel obstruction. He has mild abdominal discomfort over the wound site but is otherwise well. He denies chest pain, shortness of breath, calf pain, nausea or vomiting. His bowels have not opened since surgery. His regular medications are paracetamol and oxycodone for post-operative pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears comfortable. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. On chest auscultation, there are reduced breath sounds at both bases. The jugular venous pressure is not elevated and there is no peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous furosemide","Computed tomography of the chest","Bronchoscopy with airway suctioning","Venous blood gas analysis","Supplemental oxygen via nasal prongs at 2 L/min"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of post-operative atelectasis, which commonly occurs within 24-48 hours after abdominal surgery. The key findings are reduced oxygen saturation and decreased breath sounds at the lung bases, in the absence of other concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplemental oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E via nasal prongs is appropriate initial management to improve oxygenation while implementing other measures such as early mobilisation, deep breathing exercises, and chest physiotherapy to re-expand collapsed lung segments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with airway suctioning\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overly invasive first step for typical post-operative atelectasis. This intervention would be considered only after failure of conservative measures or in cases of major atelectasis causing significant respiratory compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as there are no clinical signs of fluid overload such as elevated jugular venous pressure or peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous blood gas analysis\u003C/strong\u003E would not change initial management and should be reserved for cases that do not improve with conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography of the chest\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for typical post-operative atelectasis. Imaging should be considered only if the patient fails to improve with conservative management or if other pathology is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of post-operative atelectasis follows a stepwise approach. Initial management includes supplemental oxygen, early mobilisation, incentive spirometry, and chest physiotherapy. These measures help to re-expand collapsed alveoli and improve ventilation-perfusion matching. If the patient does not improve with these conservative measures within 24-48 hours, or if there are signs of clinical deterioration, further investigation with chest imaging and potentially more invasive interventions may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-operative atelectasis commonly presents with reduced oxygen saturation and decreased breath sounds at the lung bases","Initial management includes supplemental oxygen and chest physiotherapy","More extensive investigation is only required if the patient does not improve with conservative measures"],"references":["Duggan M, Kavanagh BP. Atelectasis in the perioperative patient. Curr Op Anaes 2007; 20:37-42."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68011"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68011"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T18:49:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T23:43:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"212"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82941"}}}